{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474845"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:25:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:25:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12428"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12428"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.45,0.17,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4936"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35141"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4936"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12428"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20030"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"1876"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8831"},{"type":"tags","id":"11129"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8862"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42756"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44125"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44958"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/35141"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-month-old boy presents with his parents due to a fever of 38\u2103 and irritability for the past two days. His parents report that he has been pulling at his throat and ears and seems to have difficulty eating. He is not drowsy or sensitive to lights. His medical history is unremarkable and all his vaccinations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is pink on room air and he appears alert and reactive. There are no inspiratory retractions or nasal flaring. He appears in obvious pain and cannot stretch his neck to look up. He is also drooling. Otoscopy is normal. His throat examination reveals a red and swollen posterior pharynx with minimal tonsillar enlargement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute otitis media","Peritonsillar abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Acute bacterial tonsillopharyngitis","Acute epiglottitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eretropharyngeal abscess \u003C/strong\u003Eis characterised by fever, difficulty swallowing, painful swallowing, and drooling, along with pain in all neck movements due to inflammation of the pre-vertebral musculature (most commonly manifests as an inability to look up). It can cause respiratory distress if it progresses. A retropharyngeal abscess may result in a bulge in the posterior pharyngeal wall that is typically midline, and tonsillar swelling (if tonsillitis is the underlying cause), both visualised on oral cavity inspection. Additionally, there may be bilateral tender cervical lymphadenopathy. The presentation of retropharyngeal abscess\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be variable and no specific combination of signs and symptoms is diagnostic. However, generally, a febrile child with throat pain and an inability to look up is a retropharyngeal abscess until proven otherwise (which is the case in this patient). The most important feature is restricted neck movement in an unwell child with an abnormal lateral C spine X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eperitonsillar abscess\u003C/strong\u003E is due to an infection and blockage of the Weber glands, which are a group of minor mucous salivary glands located superior to the tonsil in the soft palate, their main role is to clear debris in the tonsillar area and assist digestion of food trapped in the tonsillar crypts. As these abscesses are formed within the soft palate, above the superior pole of the tonsil, they push them inferiorly and as such there is a poor view of the tonsils on examination. Tonsillitis is rarely a cause in these patients. Presentation is characterised by fever, malaise, a severely sore throat, dysphagia and odynophagia which can lead to drooling of saliva and a muffled \u0027hot potato\u0027 voice. Additionally, trismus may be seen. Contralateral deviation of the uvula is a poor associated sign as it may deviate in any direction.\u003Cbr\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute bacterial tonsillopharyngitis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by fever, tender cervical lymphadenopathy, tonsillar exudate, an absence of a cough, rhinorrhoea, or nasal congestion. The symptoms in this case could very well be mistaken for tonsillopharyngitis however the neck stiffness and frank drooling points to a condition associated with airway obstruction or deep neck space infection such as retropharyngeal abscess, peritonsillar abscess, or acute epiglottitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiglottitis\u003C/strong\u003E is typically caused by Haemophilus influenzae type B (HiB), which this child would have been vaccinated against. Given high vaccination rates against HiB, cases can be caused by Streptococcus pyogenes and Streptococcus pneumoniae. The condition is characterised by signs of respiratory distress such as inspiratory retractions, cyanosis, and nasal flaring, which are not present in this patient. Other symptoms include a sore throat, dysphagia, drooling, and a muffled voice. On examination, patients typically present with an acutely high fever of 39-40\u2103 and a toxic appearance. Although this patient displays drooling and dysphagia, the absence of respiratory distress and an acutely high fever and a toxic appearance make epiglottitis an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute otitis media\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely in this case, as the child\u0027s symptoms are not consistent with this diagnosis. Otitis media typically presents with ear pain, a red bulging and immobile tympanic membrane, and sometimes fever and irritability. However, the child\u0027s otoscopy is normal and he displays signs more suggestive of retropharyngeal abscess such as the red and swollen posterior pharynx along with fever, dysphagia, neck pain, drooling and limited neck extension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A febrile child with throat pain and an inability to look up is a retropharyngeal abscess until proven otherwise","The following features are highly suggestive of peritonsillar abscess - trismus, unilateral tonsillar inflammation with deviation of uvala to unaffected side"],"references":["National Center for Biotechnology Information. StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Chapter: Acute Pharyngitis; [cited 2022 Mar 15]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441873/","Glezen WP. Epidemiology of acute respiratory disease in children. Journal of the American Medical Association. 1969;207(4):691-6.","Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Sore Throat. [cited 2022 Mar 15]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Sore_throat/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20030"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12428"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/20030"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-04-20T09:15:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-04-20T09:15:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4936"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35141"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags",